</div>
<p>The <b>great bustard</b> (<i>Otis tarda</i>) is in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bustard" title="Bustard">bustard</a> family, the only member of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genus" title="Genus">genus</a> <i>Otis</i>. It breeds in southern and central <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a>, where it is the largest species of bird, and across temperate <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asia" title="Asia">Asia</a>. European populations are mainly resident, but Asian birds <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird_migration" title="Bird migration">move</a> further south in winter. Portugal and Spain now contain about 60% of the world's population.<sup id="cite_ref-HBW_2-0" class="reference"><a href="Otis_tarda#cite_note-HBW-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p></p>
<div id="toc" class="toc">
